{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600659/1930070601/0310.xml":{"full_text":"DEFER KEYSTONE\nELECTION INQUIRY\nCampaign Expenditure Hear\nings Will Follow Probe\nin Illinois.\nHearing of witnesses in the investiga\ntion into senatorial campaign expendi\ntures in Pennsylvania has been deferred\nuntil after the Chicago hearings, ac\ncording to an announcement made to\nday by Senator Gerald P. Nye, chair\nman of the committee.\nThe committee had intended to hear\nwitnesses from Pittsburgh and Phila\ndelphia on the expenditures for the\nDavis-Brown ticket Wednesday, but ow\ning to absence of some Senators and\npressure of other business, it was found\nimpracticable to hold the hearings\nthen. The hearings on the Illinois sit\nuation will be conducted in Chicago, be\nginning July 14. Just when it will be\npossible to clear up the Pennsylvania\nexpenditures is not predicted, except\nthat hearings on the campaign will wait\nUntil after the Illinois inquiry and will\nbegin promptly after them.\nSenator Nye said no action would be\ntaken on the case of one of its investi\ngators. W. Hunter Baldwin, alleged to\nhave been connected with the Ku Klux\nKlan, until the full committee could\npass on the matter. Mr. Baldwin made\na statement to Senator Nye and a part\nof the committee recently concerning\nhis reported connection with the Klan.\nOpinion is said to be divided in the\ncommittee as to whether he should be\nretained. He has been digging into the\nexpenditures made on behalf of Mrs.\nRuth Hanna McCormick in Cook\nCounty, and is said to have brought out\nmaterial of much use to the committee.\nSenators who hold that he should be\nretained assert that the outcry against\nhim for having been connected with the\nKlan has been raised by the friends of\nMrs. McCormick in an effort to dis\ncredit the investigation. In view of this\nthe question of retaining him may be\ncome an issue of much more importance\nthan had been indicated.\nThe committee continues to get in\nformation from New Jersey, from in\nvestigators who have been making in\nquiries there. Reports of excessive ex\npenditures in New Jersey have come to\nthe committee, but Senator Nye refuses\nto make any statement as to the nature\nof t hese reports or what candidates they\nconcern.\nDE KAY IS RELEASED\nFROM DETENTION\nAustrians Amazed at Lavish Ex-;\npenditures of Man From\nProvidence.\nBy the Assocoiated Press.\nSALZBURG, Austria, July s.\u2014John\nWesley de Kay, formerly of Providence, j\nR. 1., who was arrested Monday for al-\nleged fraud in connection with hotel I\nbills here, was tonight released from I\ndetention.\nDuring his residence in Salzburg he\naroused general curiosity by his lavish\nexpedniture and vast quantities of bag-\ngage. He gave bail and was allowed to!\njoin his family at a hotel.\nDe Kay's extradition from England I\nwas secured in 1924 by the United j\nStates Government on charges of par\nticipation in a fraud in connection with\nthe failure in 1913 of the Atlantic Na\ntional Bank of Providence.\n\u2018\u2022COSMIC FOG\u201d IS SUN\u2019S\nCORONA. OHIOAN BELIEVES\nDr. Stetson Endeavors to Deter\nmine How Close It Approaches\nthe Earth.\nBy the Associated Press.\nDELAWARE, Ohio.\u2014\u201c Cosmic fog.' 1\nhuge, irregular masses believed to be\ngas, is believed by Dr. Harlan T. Stet\nson! director of Perkins Observatory\nhere, to be the foundation of the sun\u2019s\ncorona.\nDr. Stetson is endeavoring to deter\nmine how close the \u201cfog\u201d approaches\nthe earth.\nThe sun\u2019s corona, he thinks, is the\nlight reflected from a cloud of the\n\u2022\u2018fog,\u2019' much as light is reflected by\ndust particles, which then become\nvisible.\nNEW BACTERIA MAY AID\nIN WAR AGAINST SNAKES\nBtrange Type, Fatal to Poisonous\nVarieties, Being Studied at\nlowa State.\nBy the Associated Press.\nAMES, lowa. \u2014A strange bacteria\ntype which seems deadly to poisonous\nsnakes is being studied by bacteriolo\ngists at lowa State College.\nSome time ago all the poisonous\nsnakes used in experimental work at\nthe University of Minnesota died mys\nteriously. Roger Patrick, a graduate\nstudent in bacteriology, has been en\ndeavoring to discover and grow cul\ntures of the bacteria which cau ed the\ndisease.\nSOLDIER OF FORTUNE\nWALKING BEAT AGAIN\nChicago Man Alternates Between\nServices in Army and Duty\non Force.\nCHICAGO (fP). \u2014The world is at\npeace, and Jimmy Dineen is back on\nthe force.\nThree times since he began walking\na beat. 24 years ago, Dineen has tossed\naside his copper\u2019s blue for the soldier\u2019s\nkhaki.\nOnce he went to Mexico with 1\nPershing, then he followed him to\nEurope, and his last fighting trip was\nto help the Free Staters in Ireland. i\nBut there is a liberal sprinkling of\ngray in Jimmy's hair. The old wounds\ns metimes hurt. Jimmy\u2019s 48, and the\nwife and three children want him home.\nWeaving of baskets and other wicker\npoods is being done extensively in\nl.omcs of Czechoslovakia.\nsmut mhiu\nWEf CLEAN AND PAINT YOUR FURNACE\nlor 33.50. repairs and installations: all work\nguaranteed ROBEY HEATING CO., 61 N\nst, n.e. Tel. Nat. 0635. 8*\nWANT TO HAUL FULL OR PART LOAD\nto or from New York, Richmond. Boston,\nPittsburgh and all way points; special rates.\nNATIONAL DELIVERY r ASSN.. INC 1317\nN. Y. ave. Nat. 1460. Local moving also.\nNO COLLECTION. NO CHARGE\u2014ANY Ac\ncount collected. ADEPT COLLECTION SERV\nICE, Suite 216. 805 15th st. n.w.\nWANTED\u2014RETURN LOADS\nFrom NEW YORK CITY JULY 16th\nFrom NEW YORK CITY JULY 23rd\nFrom BOSTON AUG 2 \"5\nTo NEW YORK CITY JULY 14th\nTo NEW YORK CITY .....JULY 28th\nEFECIAL RATES FOR PART LOADS TO AND\nFROM PHILADELPHIA AND NEW YORK.\nUNITED STATES STORAGE CO.. INC.,\n41R 10th St. N.W. Metropolitan 1845\nWANTED\u2014FULL OR PART LOAD FOR THE\nbelow listed cities and points en route:\nTo or from NEW YORK JULY 5. 7. 9\nTo or from CHICAGO JULY 5. 7. 9\nTo or from BOSTON JULY 5,7. 9\nAMERICAN STORAGE TRANSFER CO.\nAtlanta 1450.\nWanted\u2014Load\n\u2022-from New York. Philadelphia. Richmond.\nVa.: Chicago HI Pittsburgh. Pa., ano At\nlant c City\nTo Pittsburgh. N Y.. Cumberland. MO\nand Hair'stu Pa\nSmith\u2019s Trc\u201d f t Storage Co.\n\u201cSAVIOR OF FRANCE\u201d DEDICATES MONUMENT\n\u00a7sjg IE? flHnnP fl wf\nMarshal Joffre returning from the unveiling of a statue at Chantilly. 50 kilometers north of Paris, in front of the\nHotel du Grand Conde, which was his headquarters in the early weeks of the World War. In the foreground, left to\nright, are: Andre Maginot. minister of war; .Marshal Joffre and Marshal retain. Marshal Joffre, who is more than 78\nj'ears old, showed the effects of his recent illness.\nHOUSE IS PRAISED\nFOR AIDING HOOVER\nTilson Says Obstructive\nDemocrats in Senate\nWere Overcome.\nBy the Associated Press.\nCo-operation of the House with the\nadministration was credited yesterday\nby Representative Tilson of Connecti\ncut, the Republican leader, with en\nabling the Seventy-first Congress to\nenact most of President Hoover s major\nlegislative proposals.\nIn a statement through the Repub\nlican National Committee, Tilson re\nj viewed 18 enactments sponsored by the\nChief Executive, and said \u201ca miiitant\nI House of Representatives, imbued with\nthe will to co-operate with the admin\nistration, has enabled President Hoover\nto carry out a very comprehensive and\nfar-reaching legislative program.\u201d\nDemocrats Are Blamed.\n\u201cOvercoming persistent efforts of\nSenate Democrats at obstruction, the\nRepublican majority in the House, with\nthe aid of the Republican leaders in the\nI Senate, made possible the translation\n1 into law of practically every major pro\nposal put forward by the President,\u201d he\nsaid.\nTilson said the House had co-operated\nwith the administration in preventing\nenactment of the export debenture plan\nby the Senate.\n\u201cOnly on few occasions in recent\nI years has it been necessary for the\nHouse to become such a bulwark of de\nfense against ill-considered legislative\nefforts,\u201d he said. In addition, he said,\nthe House by sustaining a veto prevent\ned final enactment \"of unjust and dis\ncriminatory legislation affecting certain\nclasses of World War veterans.\u201d\nSome Successes Cited.\nThe Connecticut Representative cited\nthe accomplishments of Congress as I\ntariff revision; creating the Federal i\nFarm Board; the $160,000,000 tax\nreduction program: extension of the j\nI public buildings program; increasing\nFederal highway aid: enacting a vet-1\nerans\u2019 pension bill; settlement of the';\nFrench. German and Austrian war-debt I\nagreements: transferring prohibition en\nforcement to the Justice Department\nand enacting a large rivers and. harbors\nomnibus bill. I\nAmong the other achievements noted\nwere the extension of the Federal penal i\nsystem, reorganization of the Federal\nPower Commission, creation of a per\nmanent Radio Commission, appropriat\ning funds for initial work on Boulder\nCanyon Dam. providing for reappoi tion\nment and the 1930 census, establish\nment of a Bureau of Narcotics, liberal\nizing the ocean mail contracts laws and\nplacing into effect Government regula\ntion of perishable food products.\nBOOK FOR PENNY KEEPS\nSCHOOL PRESS HUMMING\nOrders for Copies of History of\nOregon Trail Overwhelm the\nPublishers.\nOMAHA, Ncbr. (/P). \u2014School children\nof the Middle West have swamped the j\npresses with orders for a penny history\nof the Oregon Trail.\nThe 10,000-word book was written by\nJ. G. Masters, principal of Omaha Cen- I\ntral High School, and is being printed\nunder Masters' supervision by the stu\ndents in the printing department of\nancther Omaha high school.\nMasters contributed the copy and the\nhigh school students are contributing\nthe labor, so that the children may\nhave a book for a penny.\nSponge Season On.\nTRIPOLI, North Africa OP) \u2014Sponge\nfishermen on this coast are in the midst I\nof their big season, lasting from April,\nto October. They find one-fifth of the\nworld supply, running up to $5,000,000\nI annually. j\nAthens College Receives SIO,OOO.\nATHENS Athens College, a\nGreco-American institution, has re-\nceived SIO,OOO from Constantine i\nj Choresmes of Alexandria for a new\nconcert hall. The college opened in j\n1925 with 20 students and now has 300, j\nD. A. V. Chief\n1 I\nIHW ;X\nCAPT. HERMAN H. WF.IMER*\nOs Chicago was elected national com\nmander of the Disabled A \u2022\u2022\u2019\u2022clean Vet\nerans at the annual t n in New\nC\u201c*--ns. a\u20147 r-*o.\nTHE SUNDAY STAR, WASHINGTON, D. C., JULY 6, 1930\u2014PART OXE.\nFrom the Front Row\nReviews and News of Washington's Theaters.\nRichard Dix at Best\nin \u201cShootin\u2019 Straight.\u201d\nWITHIN the past year or so\nthere has been a veritable\ndeluge of gangster plays\npouring into Washington,\nbut it remained for Rich\nard Dix to bring in the best that\nhas appeared to date\u2014\u201cShootin\u2019\nStraight,\u201d this week\u2019s picture at\nR-K-O Keith\u2019s.\nIn which one\nfinds Dix at his\nbest in a bang\nup movie. Swift\naction from start\nto finish, never\ndragging and\nwith human in\nterest packed in\nto the limit, car\nries Dix along\nto a new peak\nas a new type\nof lover, with a\ngreat supporting\ncast to back him\nup. Where other\ngangster pictures\nseem absurd,\nv\n\nV\nRichard Dix.\n\u201cShootln\u2019\nStraight\u201d presents itself as the real\nthing, with the minimum of blood\nand gore, but the maximum of en\ntertaining speed of movement and\nplot.\nMary Lawlor plays opposite Dix\nand she does her bit well, so much\nso that were it not for Dix she would\neasily merit major honors as the big\nstar. Few actors or actresses can\ntake any laurels of consequence from\nDix when he has been cast in a\nvehicle that calls for snap and verve,\nwith a touch cf laughter amid his\ndare-devil courage. One finds all\nthese rolled together In \u201cShootin'\nStraight.\" which isn't at all what\none might think from the title, for\npositively it is not a wild and woolly\nWestern.\nThe big shot of the big town gang\nsters (Mr. Dix), a reckless but win\nning gambler who takes the old\nheads for a ride on the baize tables,\nappears as a crap-shooting reformer\nin the production. He's no reformer\nby choice, but by accident, having\nbeen smashed up in a train wreck\nwhile possessing the wallet of a\nreformer, that had been stolen by\nhis nimble-fingered body guard as\nthe two fled inquisitive pclice.\nMary Lawlor plays the part of\nthe preacher's daughter, who nurses\nthe gang warrior back to health\nunder the impression he is the re\nformer. It will pay to watch her in\nthe future, because she's destined to\nget much higher than the role she\nhas in this picture. She is an\nactress.\nThe story carries these two into\nplenty of action because of Mary's\nbrother, who has given some I. O. U.'s\nto the town's gambling king, who\ndesires Mary. As the reformer. Dix\nshoots dice with the gambler, win\nning of course.\nEventually It becomes necessary for\nthe b;gus reformer who is dodging\nthe law to clean out the den of the\ngambler and win back the brother's\nnotes. He does all of that to reach\na happy ending.\nAn old story, to be sure, but one\ncan forget it in the acting of Dix\nand Mary Lawlor. There are enr.ugh\nnew situations and lines in the play\nto lift it from the depths to a high\nniche of its own.\nShort subjects, newsreels, a comedv\nand the animated \"talkie\u201d cartoons\nround out the bill D. J. K.\n\u201cOne Rontantic Night\u201d\nGood, But Less So Than \u201cThe Swan.\u201d\nCOMPARISONS being inevitable,\nit seems only just to report that.\n\u201cOne Romantic Night,\u201d the screen\nversion of Ferenc Molnar\u2019s play,\n\u201cThe Swan,\u201d now at Loews Palace,\nIs not up to the standard set by its\noriginal.\nThe picture, however, is distinctly\nabove the average and one that Is\nmade often important through the\nactions of its players.\nNot only does the film tell of the\nnow classic story of the young\nprincess who fell in love with the\ntutor, but it brings Lillian Gish\nback to the screen with a new per\nsonality (as advertised) and a new\nvoice. Somehow the .transition to\nthis so-called \u201cnew personality\u201d\ndoes not seem especially marked.\nMiss Gish is still at her best when\nshe is rolling her eyes heavenward\nand fixing her thoughts presumably\non the idyllic beauties of this world.\nShe incorporates, it is true, a (cer\ntain roguishness into her character\nization, but the effect never allows\none to believe that she is at all dif\nferent from what she used to be.\nHer voice furthermore is not just\nwhat might have been expected. Per\nhaps due to the microphone, it is not\ncontinually smooth, nor always con\nvincingly youthful. Miss Gish may still\nbe found to be as fragile, as ethereal\nand as wistful as when D. W. Grif\nfith first precipitated her to the\nbrink of a waterfall. Every now and\nthen, when caught in repose, she\nphotographs quite beautifully.\nSetting aside the fact that this\nfilm makes many departures from\nthe text of the play, peeling off\nmuch of the original froth and\nveneer, one may say that, for screen\nentertainment purposes, it has un\nusually auspicious idiosyncrasies.\nThese are due mainly to the antics\nof Marie Dressier, who overacts and\noveracts continually, but neverthe\nless is as funny as always. Playing\nthe part of the scheming mother,\nwho is trying to snatch a prince\nand a throne for her daughter, she\nsummons up all the powers of her\nburlesque drolleries and lays them\non with uncommon energy. Although\ndevotees of the play complain that\nshe raises havoc with her part, one\nmight as well admit that If she\nhadn\u2019t tried so hard \u201cOne Romantic\nNight\u201d might have been a more\nhonest), if not so amusing an affair.\nThose who aontribute much to\nI\nthe picture\u2019s success are O. P. Heg\ngie. Conrad Nagel, who could have\nbeen a trifle more emotional as the\ntutor, and Rod La Rocque, for love\nof whom the princess ran off to\nSouth America, or thought she did.\nDave Schooler and June Carr, a\nyoung lady who dances very nicely,\nare headliners in this week's stage\nrevue called \u201cSteel Blues.\u201d They\nare supported by a team of excellent\nacrobatic dancers, Les Ghellis, and\na swarm of Chester Hale girls.\nThe ever-popular Dick Leibert,\nraising the roof with his organ selec\ntions; short subjects, newsreels and\nthe Palace Orchestra complete a\ngood bill. E. de S. M.\nGEORGIAN CHARGED\nWITH KILLING MAN\nTimber Estimator Is Alleged to\nHave Shot Camp Super\nintendent.\nBy the Associated Press.\nBRYSON CITY. N. C July 5 \u2014W. B\nGriffin of Georgia was in the Swain\nCounty jail here today charged with\nmurder for shooting Prentice Boston\nof Stubensville, Tenn., yesterday at a\ncamp of the Tennessee Park Commis\nsion. on top of Cllngmans Dome, noted\ngreat Smoky Mountains peak,\nj Boston was in charge of the camp\nand Griffith w-as employed by the com\nmission as a timber estimator,\nj Millard Smith, a friend of Boston,\nsaid Griffin came into a tent where\nhe was chatting with Boston and shot\nthe latter without warning. Boston\nj died immediately.\ni Smith seized Griffin's weapon and\ni then forced him to accompany him\nhere, where he was lodged in jail,\nj Griffin weuld make no statement.\nI Cllngmans Dome is on the dividing\ni line between North Carolina and Ten- I\nnessee.\nSNAKES DISAPPEARING\nIN ISLAND OF HAITI\nRepublic Soon to Resemble Erin\nin Being Free of\nReptiles.\nCAPE HAITIEN. Haiti CFt\u2014TliLs\ntropical Island, which is about tne same\nsize as Ireland, but always greener, be\ncause Winter never comes, soon will\nequal the Emerald Isle in re\nspect.\nSnakes are rapidly disappearing in\nboth Haiti and the Dominican Repub\nlie, although no St. Patrick has ap\npeared to drive them into the sea.\nWhen Christopher Columbus landed\nhere there were quite a few snakes,\ni although none was poisonous. The\nreptiles have been gradually extermi\nnated as agriculture developed and only\nsmall species remain. a\nMINIATURE GAS ENGINE\nUSED TO RUN TOY BOAT\nj Power Propels Small Craft at Rate\nof Four Miles Per Hour, Is\nClaim.\nSEATTLE. Wash. (A 3 ).\u2014What he be\nlieves is the smallest gasoline engine in\nthe world has been built by Daniel\nCalkin of the University of Washing\nj ton.\nCalkin built the motor, which he\nestimates develops about one-sixteenth\nhorsepower, to run a small toy boat\n1 about 30 inches long. It operates on\ni the same principles as an outboard\nmotor, and travels about 4 miles an\nhour.\nj The 3-inch flywheel makes about\ni 1,000 revolutions a minute. An eye\nj dropper is used to fill the gasoline\ntank.\nI Calkin spent about 600 hours build\ning the motor, but in money it cost\nhim only about 75 cents.\nExiled Statesman\nfir\nSANTIAGO ALBA,\nExiled Spanish Liberal leader, whose\nrecent conversations with King Alfonso\nin Paris caused considerable comment\nIn Spanish political circles.\n\u2014Associated Press Photo.\nLURE OF HAWAII\nADDS POPULATION\nIslands Report Increase of\n43.9 Per Cent\u2014Honolulu\nBoasts 137,582.\nBy the Associated Press.\nA thriving Hawaii was shown in fig\nures announced by the United States\nCensus Bureau yesterday.\nThe lure of the land of the lei\nbrought its 1930 population total up to\n255,912. a 43.9 per cent increase over\n1920. Continental United States, half\nreported, increased by but 17.4 per cent.\nHad Hawaii been entered in that list of\nStates, thus far reported, she would\nhave ranked next to California, the top\nnotcher, in percentage of increase.\nHonolulu, the largest city of the\nIslands, entered the list of cities of more\nthan 100,000 inhabitants with a 65.1\nper cent increase, outdistancing San\nJuan, Porto Rico, which entered that\nlist with a 60.3 per cent increase Hono\nlulu\u2019s present population is 137,582; San\nJuan\u2019s is 114,585.\nDuring the decade just past. Honolulu\noutgrew Evansville, Ind.; Port Wayne,\nInd.; Canton, Ohio; Waterbury, Conn.;\nJacksonville. Fla.; Somerville. Mass.;\nErie, Pa.: Utica, N. Y.; Lawrence, Mass.;\nElizabeth, N, J.; Tacoma, Wash.; Du\nluth, Minn.; Lynn, Mass.; Yonkers, N.\nY.; Kansas City, Kans.; Spokane,\nWash.; Reading, Pa.: Cambridge, Mass.;\nWilmington, Del.; Lowell, Mass.; Nor\nfolk. Va.; Camden. N. J.; Pall River,\nMass., and New Bedford, Mass.\nPopulation of Ilil City was announced\nas 19,468. an 86 per cent increase.\nPopulations of the various Islands of\nthe Hawaiian group were announced as\nfollows; Oahu Island, 202,887; Hawaii\nIsland, 73,325; Maul, 48,756; Kauai, 35,-\n806; Molokai, 5,032; Lanai, 2,356; Nihau,\n136; Midway, 36, and Kalioolawe, 2.\nKahoolawe\u2019s announced population\nfigure, 2, sets a new minimum for the\n1930 census and shows a 33.3 per cent\ndecrease, the 1920 population of that\nisland being 3. In 1910 the population\nwas 2. Experts agree it would take con\nsiderable research to find the equal of\nKahoolawe\u2019s record, the closest parallel,\nperhaps, being the population of the\nGarden of Eden in the days of Adam\nand Eve.\nMidway Island, gaining 6, won back\nall her losses of the World War decade.\nIn 1910, Midway had 35 Inhabitants; in\n1920 but 31, an 11.4 per cent decrease.\nBut she now tallies her greatest recorded\ni population\u201436.\nCUBA PAYS $350,000\nIN HARRAH RAIL CASE\nDestruction of Line by Private In\nterests Arbitrated and\nQuickly Settled.\nBy the Associated Press.\nHAVANA. July 5. \u2014Prompt settlement\nof the claim of Charles H. Harrah\nagunst the Cuban government, arbi\ntrated Thursday, for *350.000, was re\ncorded here today when Ambassador\nHarry Guggenheim placed in the mails\na check for that amount, handed him\nby the Cuban state department.\nHarrah s case was based on the con\ntention that a narrow-gauge railway\nwhich he had owned at Marianao was\ndestroyed by private interests. His\noriginal claim was for $9.000.000, but\nthis sum was reduced two-thirds during\nthe first meeting of Cuban and United\nStates arbitrators. Now, later, further\nreduced, Ambassador Guggenheim mail\ned the check to the United States\nDepartment cf State, and. after arbitra\ntion expenses are deducted. Mr. Harrah,\nwho is now in Havana, will be paid.\nMISSISSIPPI OUSTS\n15 FROM COLLEGES\nTrustees of University Dismiss 4\nProfessors and 11 on Faculty\nat Women's School.\nBy the Associated Press.\nGULFPORT. Miss.. July s.\u2014Tiustees\nof the University ui Mississippi and af\nfiliated colleges, meeting here today,\ndismissed four professors at the univer-\nI sity and 11 members of the faculty at\nMississippi State College for Women in\na general revision of faculties.\nReasons for the removals were not\nI made public.\ni Those removed at the university are\nO. E Tomlinson, assistant piofessor of\nengineering; P. K. Reese, and J. T.\nAtkins, assistant professor of mathe\nmatics. and L. E. Thacher, organist and\nprofessor of biology.\nWORLD FAIR TO REVIVE\nHUMAN GAS METERS\nI\ni 1933 Exhibition to Depict Scenes\nWith Gas Inspectors Being Only\nCheck on Overconsumption.\nCHICAGO (<P). \u2014The first American\ngas meter was a man.\nWhen illuminating gas was first in\ntroduced there were no meters, but cus\ntomers agreed to turn it off after a\nspecified hour.\nGas inspectors were appointed. Rec\nords show that on their rounds these\ninspectors frequently rapped on win\ndows to remind their cuseomers that\nthey were using overtime gas.\nThese old scenes will be reproduced\nin the scientific exhibits at the 1933\nWorld Fair here.\nHUGE HISTORY COMPILED\nConsists of 800 Volumes Totaling\n130,000 Pages.\nSHANGHAI \"The Twenty-four\nHistories of Chinese Dynasties,\u201d all fac\nsimiles of ancient editions, has gone to\nthe publisher. It will be probably the\nlargest history set ever compiled, com\nprising 800 volumes and totaling 130,000\npages.\nAbjures Monroe Doctrine.\nMEXICO CITY (jP).\u2014The Monroe\nDoctrine should be substituted by a\n\"real and just\u201d pact binding the Amer\nicas on eoual terms, El Universal stfys\neditorially. The newspaper adds that\nSpanish American peoples resent the\n\u201d\u00a3rotectorate2_of_the_United_States __\nHot Weather\nand\nShowers\nSuggest\nThe SkuySttNiNG\nAny\nHead\n\u2014and all types of complete show\ners. Installed by your Plumber.\nE. G. Schafer Co.\n215 13th St. N.W.\nA REAL GINGERBREAD HOUSE\n-H'.. \u2018'y\n\u25a0PAm\u2019gif] j -Vv\n\u2022SSSSihSmSSSSSSSSS\nSo charmed was F. 11. Bennett. New York manufacturer, with the ginger\nbread house in the opera \"Hansel and Gretel\" that lie hired the designer of the\nset to make him one on his estate in Hamburg. N. J. And here it is, an honest\nto-goodness gingerbread house of many-colored stone, which is to be open at\nall times to \u201cchildren of ail ages.\u201d \u2014Associated Press Photo. I\nAMERICANS JOIN LLOYD GEORGE\nIN PLEA FOR CHURCH PLACE AIM\nInternational Congregational Meeting\nHears ex-Premier of England Warn\nof War Activities.\nI By the\nBOURNEMOUTH. England, July 5.\n\u2014Two American clergymen voiced ap\nj peals for co-operation between the\nchurches of the world at the Interna\ntional Congregational meeting today.\nThe ministers, assembled from many\ncountries, heard a stirring plea by\nDavid Lloyd George, former British\nprime minister and Liberal leader, for\nchurch aid in dispelling international\ndistrust and suspicion.\nDr. W E. Barton of Foxboro, Mass.,\npastor emeritus of the First Church of\nOak Park. 111., and former moderator\nof the National Congregational Coun\ncil, a noted churchman and author of\nbiblical and other publications, speak\ning on church unity, said the first need\nwas to promote a co-operation, and\neven organic union, of the bodies which\nhad the most in common. Not a uni\nformity, but a unity which permitted\nwide diversities was wanted, Dr. Bar\nton said\nRefers to Lambeth.\nReferring to the meeting of bishops\nof the Angelican Church at I.ambeth,\nDr. Barton said the Congregationalists\nwere just as competent as the Lam\nbeth bishops to say on what conditions\nthe union of the future must be\nfounded.\n\u201cAnd whether the Lambeth bishops\nsay they wiU receive us or not,\" Dr.\nBarton said, we will not outlaw them,\ni If they draw a circle that keeps us out,\nj we will draw one that takes them in.\nI There we will siand, Lambeth agreeing\nor dissenting, as the case may be. May\nthe Lord bless Lambeth and give to its\nbishops more wisdom than this council\nhas sometimes had. to say nothing\nabout that degree of wisdom which has\nhitherto been withheld from Lambeth.\u201d\nDr. W. E. Gilroy of Boston, Mass.,\nsaid the Congregationalists were not so\nmuch concerned about unity with the\nChurch of England as unity among\nthe free churches. The best way to make\nprogress, Dr. Gilroy said, was along the\nlines of federation. In America, he\nsaid, they were building up larger com\nmunities and greater cooperations\namong the free churches, and greater\nprogress would be made in that direc\ntion than by scrapping their congrega\ntional liberties.\nResolution Is Adopted.\nA resolution adopted by the council\nwas sent to the Archbishop of Canter\nbury \"praying for the day when diffi\nculties in the way of complete fellow\nship would iic removed.\" Another reso\nlution sent to ldm and to the bishops\nassehibliitg for tne Lambeth conference\nread:\n\"We have prayed that out of your\ndeliberations.there may come decisions\nwhich shall be for the good ntfi only\nof your own great church but for the\nblessing of Christendom.\u201d\nTiie resolution further dealt with the\nsubject of unity.\nLloyd George, after asserting that\nevery country in the world was pre\nparing> for war, and that there were\nmore trained men for war in Europe,\nj Asia and America than before the ca\ntastrophe of 1914, declared;\nHears Sound of Weapons.\n\u201cI speak from personal experience\nwhen I say that althoueh I have gone\nto live in a quiet place in Surrey.\nI hear every day the rattle of machine\nguns in one camp, the hoarse roar\nof cannon in another, and, carried\nby the westerly breeze, I hear the boom\nof naval artillery from the direction\nof Portsmouth, and the drone of air\nplanes.\n\u201cThat is going on in every civilized\nland on earth. It is really time the\nINSPECT TODAY\nTHE NEW\nENGLISH HOMES\nin\nWoodley Park\nThe purchasers of these\nhomes will be assured of\na delightfully cool home,\nand yet live in a close-in\nlocation\u2014within 8 min\nutes of downtown.\nExhibit Home\n2924 Cortland PL\nTo reach: Drive west on\nCathedral Ave. from Conn.\nAve. to 29th St., turn right to\nCortland PI.\nH. G. SMITHY CO.\nSucceeaora to Buiinass of\nN. L. Sansbury Co., Inc.\n1418 Eye St. N.W. Natl. 5904\nchurches took this tiling in hand. I\ndon't know who else can do it\n\"The international situation is bad.\niWe are building up barriers against\ni each other, putting up fences against\neach other and restrictions against each\nother. We are blockading each other,\nand we are trying to starve each other,\nj Trade is threatened as if it were con\ntraband. The atmosphere is poisoned\nj with suspicion and mistrust.\n\"Let us have brotherhood. It is only\nthe Christian churches that can do it.\nIt is for you to do it.\u2019\u2019\nHUNGARIANS STUDY\nBRIAND UNION PLAN\nEethlen Indicates Change in Ver\nsailles Pact Terms Will Be\nNecessary.\nBy the Associated Pres*.\nBUDAPEST, July s.\u2014The European\nfederal union scheme of Foreign Min\nister Briand of France was discussed 1\ntoday by the Foreign Affairs Commit\ntee of the Upper House of the Hun\ngarian Parliament, which examined the\nconditions under which Hungary might\nco-operate in it.\nPremier Batlilen said that in draft\ning the official reply of the government j\nlie would take care of Hungary\u2019s politi\ncal and economic interests. Her prin\ncipal requirement is a change in some\nof the provisions of the Versailles treaty. I\nAlbert Berzevicy, chairman of tlie\ncommittee, pointed out the great merits\nof the Briand plan.\nSCIENTISTS SEEK PRETTY\nFISH ON REMOTE ISLAND\nField Museum Organizes Expedi\ntion Headed by Philip Chancellor\nto Collect Rare Specimens.\nCHICAGO 04 s ).\u2014An expedition to\ni Aitutaki, a remote island of the Pa\ncific Ocean, has been organized by the\n1 Field Museum. Scientists, led by Philip\nM. Chancellor of Santa Barbara, Calif.,\nwill collect beautiful fish which abound\ni around the coral reefs of the island.\nRarely has a white man set foot on\nthe island. It is populated by a few\nnatives, whose lives are unmodified by\nI civilization. Underwater pictures, both\nmotion and still, will be made.\ncmncmnncLnciririF\nJJ U*S Emm Kadi laJ Iwr M\n[j\n!!n Come (tut trhere it is cool and healthy\nS DETACHED HOMES\nAT ROW HOUSE PRICES I\ngj HOMES OF 100 NEW IDEAS\nI lUutli Unnitrtiujf ij\n2 1st and Randolph Sis. N.E. 5l\n'S l Hjji\nA Beautiful I\\eiv Restricted Subdivision 2\nof Over 100 Detached Brick Homes\n|-1 i a, id 8 Rooms Allic Play Rooms f 2\n1 Colored Porcelain Pool Room for Adults 2\nm 1 Rath and Kitchen Carafes r 2\n3 Fixtures Open Fireplaces 2\nI 2 We Will Be Looking f( r You This Evening j\u00a3j\n1 3 Drive (tut Rhode Island Avenue to 22nd Street S.E. \u2014then P 2\nj j north to Randolph Street and left on Randolph to 21st. 3\ni J Onen and Lighted Until 9 O'Clock P.M. J\nH.R.HoWENSTEfN\u00ae!\nw incorpobaho ygSg J\n0)1 H STREET NORTHWEST jj\nINDUSTRY\u2019S HUMAN\nSIDE TO BE TOPIC\nSouthern Conference Will\nBegin July 17 at Blue\nRidge, N. C.\nBy the Associated Press.\nATLANTA, Ga., July 5. The pro\ngrame lor the eleventh annual session\nof the Southern Conference on Human\nRelations In Industry, to be held at\nBlue Ridge, N. C\u201e July 17 to 20. was\nannounced here today by E. G. Wilson,\nexecutite secretary of the industrial\ndepartment of the Y. M. C. A.\nMr. Wil.son said these conferences have\nincreased in Interest until there is an\nannual attendance of about 500 indus\ntrial leaders of the South, who engage\nin discussions of problems pertaining to\nall phases of industry. Among the sub\njects considered are social service work,\nsafety measures, the public's relation to\nindustrial problems and the business\noutlook in the South.\nSpeakers at the conference this year\nwill include Morris Bush, Birmingham,\npresident of the Alabama By-Products\nCo.; Col. P. H. Callahan, Louisville,\nKy:, president of the Louisville Varnish\nCo. and a national figure in the Knights\nof Columbus organization; Robert\nLathan, editor of the Asheville Citizen;\nRoy Wright, New York, managing edi\ntor of the Railway Age; Dr. Harry\nMyers, Dayton. Ohio, of the Frigidalre\nCorporation; J. E. Lenhardt of the\ni Standard Oil Co. of New Jersey; Seth\nW. Candee, New York, personnel direc\ntor of the Tidewater Oil Co.; J. B.\nWoodward of the Newport News Ship\nbuilding Co.: T. L. Hines, plant man\nager of the Dupont Rayon Co. at Old\nHickory, Tenn.. and Dr. Henry M. Ed\nmonds, Birmingham, pastor of the\nIndependent Presbyterian Church.\nJEWS CELEBRATE\nREGION OPENING\nThird Autonomous Area in Ukrainia\nEmbraces 11 Villages, With\n13,000 Population.\nMOSCOW, July 5 Jewish Telegraph\nAgency).\u2014More than 10.000 Jewish and\nnon-Jewish peasants left their work In\nthe fields today and walked miles to\nwitness the ceremonies in the old Jewish\ncolony of Islutsehista officially opening\nI the third Jewish autonomous region In\ni Ukrainia.\nRed flags waved from every roof and\nfrom a huge dais in the center of the\ncolony.\nThe speakers included officials of the\nUkrainian and central soviet govern\nments. The new autonomous Jewish\nregion embraces nine Jewish and two\nUkrainian villages with a population of\n9.000 Jews and 4.000 Ukrainians. It L<\nsituated in the Krlvorog district and\nconsists of old pre-war Jewish colonies\nand new Agro-joint colonies.\nHUSBAND GREETING WIFE\nENDS HER LIFE IN CRASH\nMachine Swerves as He Waves and\nCars Overturn, Woman Dying\nand Man Hurt.\nBy the Associated Press.\nFLORENCE. S. C\u201e July 5 \u2014Dr. G,\nF. Sikes. 50, Salemburg. N. C.. physi\ncian, drove his automobile into that\nof Us wife while answering a call to\nday. fatally injuring Mrs. Sikes.\nThe physician was passing Mrs Sikes*\ncar and waved a greeting. As he did\nso his automobile swerved into hers and\nI both cars overturned. Dr. Sikes sus\nj tained a fractured shoulder blade.\nMILAN HAS TOY FAIR\nThousands Visit Exposition in Ital\nian City.\nMILAN, Italy (A Pi. \u2014The Second Na\ntional Toy Exposition has just ended\nhere. Thousands of toys of thousands\ni of varieties have been on display for a\nj fortnight and tens of thousands of\nchildren, grown-ups. merchants and\nmanufacturers have come to see them.\n\nEDISON\nand\nSTEWART WARNER\nRADIO SETS\nSold on Easy Terms\nYour Old Set in Trade\nThere arc none Better and\nFew as Good.\nGIBSON\u2019S\n917 G St. N.W.\nva mmm mm*\nA-3","height":"25050","width":"19404"}}
